I don't mean to derail, but the thing I dislike about javascript libraries is the deception. $ looks really cheap! So lets use it as we would to reference a variable...<p>for(var e=0;e<10;e++) {
    $('foo').doSomething();
}<p>It's not obvious from that code that $ is a relatively expensive function, and you'd be far better doing.<p>var foo = document.getElementById("foo");
for(var e=0;e<10;e++) {
    foo.doSomething();
}<p>I think that point alone creates poor, slow code.
